# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buttermilk
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The a2 Milk Company and some companies producing goat's milk products claim that milk containing A1 proteins is harmful, but there has been no widely accepted scientific work identifying a link between A1 protein and any adverse effect on health.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A1 and A2 beta-casein are genetic variants of the beta-casein milk protein that differ by one amino acid.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A genetic test, developed by the a2 Milk Company, determines whether a cow produces A2 or A1 type protein in its milk.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In the 1980s, medical researchers began to explore whether some peptides (including peptides from casein) that are created during digestion might have negative or positive health effects.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The research generated interest in the media, as well as among the scientific community and entrepreneurs.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] If it were indeed true that BCM-7 is harming humans, this would be an important public health issue, as well as a commercial opportunity.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Cow milk is about 87 percent water and 13 percent solids, a combination of fat, carbohydrates in the form of lactose, minerals, and protein.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] About 30 to 35 percent of the casein (equivalent to two teaspoons per quart of milk) is beta-casein, of which there are several varieties, determined by the genes of the cow.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The most common of these variants are A1 and A2 proteins, named for the order in which they were identified by scientists.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The sole difference is that one of the 209 amino acids that make up the beta-casein proteins, a proline, occurs at position 67 in the chain of amino acids that make up the A2 beta-casein, while in A1 beta-casein, a histidine occurs at that position.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Studies in cells found that digestive enzymes that cut up proteins interact with beta-casein precisely at that location, so that A1 and A2 beta-casein proteins are processed differently.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A seven-amino acid peptide, beta-casomorphin-7, can be cut away from the A1-beta-casein protein by those enzymes, but the enzymes cannot cut the A2 protein at that location, so BCM-7 is not formed from A2 proteins.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Studies in humans have not consistently found that BCM-7 is formed in the human digestive system.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] BCM-7 can also be created during the fermentation of milk or through the process by which cheese is made; those same processes can also destroy BCM-7.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The percentage of the A1 and A2 beta-casein protein varies between herds of cattle, and also between countries and provinces.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] While African and Asian cattle continue to produce only A2 beta-casein, the A1 version of the protein is common among cattle in the western world.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The A1 beta-casein type is the most common type found in cow's milk in Europe (excluding France), the US, Australia and New Zealand.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] On average, more than 70 percent of Guernsey cows produce milk with predominantly A2 protein, while among Holsteins and Ayrshires between 46 and 70 percent produce milk containing both the A1 and A2 proteins.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The A2 Corporation was founded in New Zealand in 2000 to commercialise a genetic test to determine whether a cow will produce milk without the A1 protein, and to market the milk it produces as A2 or A2 MILK.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In 2003, A2's website said: "Beta casein A1 may be a primary risk factor for heart disease in adult men, and also be involved in the progression of insulin-dependent diabetes in children" and the CEO had linked A1 to schizophrenia and autism.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A2 Corporation also petitioned the Food Standards Australia New Zealand regulatory authority to require a health warning on ordinary milk.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The company initially marketed its milk as containing no A1 protein, but in 2003 the New Zealand Commerce Commission tested the milk and found some A1 protein in it, and forbade the company from saying the milk had no A1 protein.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In April 2014, A2 Corporation changed its name to The a2 Milk Company Limited, and at that time had about 8% market share of the milk products market in Australia.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] "A2 MILK" are trademarks held by the A2 Milk Company.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A2 Corporation licensed patents filed in the 1990s by the New Zealand Dairy Board, and filed its own patents on genetic tests to determine what form of beta-casein cows produce in milk, and concerning supposed adverse health consequences of milk containing both the A1 and A2 proteins.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The a2 Milk Company focused its initial efforts on urging farmers to undertake breeding programs to develop herds that would produce milk with predominantly A2 protein.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The launch of the milk was delayed by opposition from Fonterra, which had contracts with about 98% of New Zealand dairy farms.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] These contracts were protected under New Zealand law by the Dairy Industry Restructuring Act of 2001.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The litigation threatened New Zealand's economy and international reputation as at the time Fonterra was responsible for 20% of New Zealand's exports.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The press over the litigation and public concern over the claims of A2 Corporation led the New Zealand Food Safety Authority and the Ministry of Health and the Food Standards Australia and New Zealand to issue reports and statements confirming the safety of conventional milk.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A2 Corporation obtained agreements with enough dairy farmers to launch its milk in New Zealand at the end of April 2003.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In the middle of 2003, both founders of the company died.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In July, Paterson was found dead in his hotel room during a business trip at the age of 50.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Corran McLachlan died of cancer at the age of 59.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] By end of 2003 the weakened A2 Corporation had withdrawn the litigation against Fonterra and negotiations had resumed.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Meanwhile, the first time milk with predominantly A2 protein was marketed anywhere in the world was in March 2003 in Australia, by a dairy farm unaffiliated with A2 Corporation, run by the Denniston family.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Shortly thereafter, an Australian company called A2 Dairy Marketers licensed patent rights and the A2 trademark from A2 Corporation and started offering Australian dairy farmers a premium price for their milk, if it was shown to be pure A1 protein-free milk.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The Dennistons and A2 Dairy Marketers marketed milk with predominantly A2 protein boldly, touting its safety and the dangers of standard milk.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] However, Australian laws forbid companies from making misleading health claims about food and, in September 2004, A2 Dairy Marketers in Australia was fined $15,000 after it pleaded guilty to six breaches of those laws.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The company, which had been in a tenuous financial situation since beginning trading in May 2004, went into administration in October, and was liquidated in November, owing farmers and processors tens of thousands of dollars.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A $1.27 million federal government grant awarded to the company in August as part of the Regional Partnerships Program was also cancelled.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A2 Corporation set up a new subsidiary and licensee, A2 Australia, to market and produce its product.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A2 Australia established new contracts with the dairy farmers who had A1 protein-free herds, promising better payment terms — a week in advance instead of once per month, after shipment.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In December, A2 Corporation sold its interests in A2 Australia to Fraser & Neave, a food marketing giant in Asian markets, for about $1.1 million.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A2 Corporation had lost about $1.3 million for 2004, the same as it had lost the year before; the sale allowed A2 Corporation to rely on Fraser & Neave to build the Australian and Asian businesses.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A2 Corporation focused on recovering from the deaths of its founders organizationally and financially, relied on its New Zealand licensees to develop the New Zealand market, and turned its focus to developing overseas markets.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] As A2 Corporation grew its business, opposition to A2 Corporation's claims played out in the media.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Dairy Australia, the national association of the Australian dairy industry, and market competitors like Parmalat have consistently said that there is no evidence to suggest A1 proteins are dangerous and have warned that criticism of normal milk is damaging the entire dairy industry.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In 2006, A2 Corporation was on sound enough footing to buy back A2 Australia from Fraser & Neave.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In 2006, it lost about $1 million, after having lost $9 million the year before, but revenues had approximately doubled.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In that year it warned shareholders not to expect profit for another three years.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] It asked the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) to undertake such a review.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The EFSA report, released in 2009, found that "a cause and effect relationship is not established between the dietary intake of BCM-7 (beta-casomorphin-7), related peptides or their possible protein precursors and non-communicable diseases".
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In February 2011, A2 Corporation announced it had a made a profit over a half-year for the first time; in the six months ending 31 December 2010, it made a net $894,000, or 17 cents/share.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In December 2012, A2 Corporation announced it would attempt to raise $20 million and list on the New Zealand Stock Exchange main board, and that it would use the funds to grow its Chinese infant formula and UK milk businesses under the a2 and a2 MILK brands.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A2 Corporation changed its name to The a2 Milk Company Limited in April 2014, and at that time had about 8% market share of the milk products market in Australia.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Other products produced using milk with predominantly A2 protein were developed, including thickened cream, infant formula, ice cream, yogurts, and other dairy products.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The a2 Milk Company announced in November 2014 that it had begun the application process for a dual listing on the Australian Securities Exchange in a bid to open its register to Australian investors and boost the liquidity of its shares.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The company said it expected a listing to be completed by March 2015.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] ISI had paid A2 $500,000 in license fees by the end of 2004.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] ISI acquired Twinlab in September 2003, followed by another string of acquisitions in the dietary supplement market.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In June 2005, ISI and A2 Corporation agreed to form a joint venture, A2 Milk Company LLC.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A2 Corporation invested $400,000, and ISI assigned the license agreement to the new company.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In April 2007, A2 Corporation licensed rights to the Original Foods Company, whose branding the milk with predominantly A2 protein product would carry, and in which the product would be sold in several midwestern states through the Hy-Vee supermarket chain under the a2 and a2 MILK brands.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Braum's, a chain of dairy and fast-food stores found mostly in the American Southwest, independently developed a herd of A2 cattle at its primary farm in Tuttle, Oklahoma over a period of 12 years.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Since 2020, the company exclusively sells A2 milk to consumers and also uses it in other dairy products, such as ice cream and cheese.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] A2 Corporation formed a joint venture with a major British milk supplier, Müller Wiseman Dairies, in November 2011 to process, market, and sell its milk with predominantly A2 protein products in Britain and Ireland.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In June 2014, the a2 Milk Company reported it had 20 dedicated farms supplying milk for processing in the UK.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In its first year, the milk recorded £1 million in sales through 1,000 stores.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In January 2014, the a2 Milk Company exited its joint venture with Müller Wiseman Dairies by acquiring MWD's stake for a "nominal" amount.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In October 2019, the a2 Milk Company announced that it had decided to "discontinue a2 milk in the UK" and its products would only be available until the end of November 2019.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The first consignments of the a2 Milk Company's infant formulas were sent to China in 2013.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Shipments were interrupted for two months starting in April 2014 when the Chinese government introduced strict new import regulations for infant formula in response to the 2008 Chinese milk scandal, in which more than 300,000 infants were poisoned by contaminated milk formula.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In 2018, the a2 Milk Company was fined 100,100 yuan for breaching Chinese child image advertising rules by using An Ji, son of Hu Ke and Sha Yi, in their advertising when he was under 10.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The Brazilian Association of Allergy and Immunology found that about 350,000 individuals in Brazil are allergic to beta-caseins.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] As of 2017, about 700 litres of milk a day were produced in Brazil through Gir cows, a breed originally procured from India, but which are now also being exported to India.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In Turkey, A2 milk is sold as "Jersey" milk primarily by the company Elta Ada which operates an organic farm located on the island of Gökçeada in the province of Çanakkale.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) reviewed the scientific literature and published their results in 2009.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] As part of their evaluation, the EFSA looked at the laboratory studies that had been done on bovine β-casomorphin 7 (BCM-7) that found that BCM-7 can act as a weak opioid receptor agonist.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The EFSA found no relationship between any disease and drinking milk with the A1 protein.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] In most of the animal studies, BCM-7 was not administered orally, as humans would be exposed to it, but rather was given to animals by injection into the peritoneal cavity or directly into the spinal cord or brain.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] The EFSA study emphasized the dangers of drawing conclusions from correlations identified in epidemiological studies and the dangers of not reviewing all the evidence at hand.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Reviews conducted in 2005 and 2009 found no demonstration that consuming milk with A1 casein causes diabetes.
[src:buttermilk/a2-milk] Milk with predominantly A2 protein is not a milk substitute for infants with cow milk protein allergies.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] Historically, the Anchor brand of milk products in New Zealand was owned by the New Zealand Dairy Group, which merged with Kiwi Co Operative in 2001 to form Fonterra.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] As the merger would leave New Zealand with virtually no competition in the domestic dairy sector, government legislation was required for Fonterra to be formed.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] One of the requirements was that Fonterra must divest its strongest domestic brand, Anchor, in the New Zealand market.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] This did not affect the brand internationally.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] The brand was sold to what is currently Goodman Fielder.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] Between 2001 and 2005, Fonterra grew one of their smaller milk brands which was originally only available in the South Island of New Zealand, 'Meadow Fresh Milk', into a nationwide brand which provided good competition to the Anchor brand of milk products.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] In 2005, Fonterra did a brand swap with what is now Goodman Fielder, swapping Meadow Fresh for Anchor, allowing Fonterra to again align its international and domestic dairy brands.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] On 11 November 2024, Fonterra confirmed that it would be selling several of its consumer brands including Anchor.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] On 22 August 2025, Fonterra confirmed it would sell Anchor along with several consumer brands and its processing operations in Australia and Sri Lanka to French dairy company Lactalis for NZ$3.845 billion, subject to a shareholder vote and regulatory approval.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] Fresh Anchor Milk products available in New Zealand are manufactured and marketed by Fonterra Brands, a division of Fonterra.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] The main plant that processes Anchor milk in New Zealand is in Takanini, Auckland.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] In addition to the common varieties with differing percentages of milk fat, they also offer "Anchor-Xtra", with extra calcium (marketed to "extra active" parents), and "Mega Milk", with extra vitamins, as well as extra calcium, marketed for children.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] In 2013, the Anchor brand was released in China.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] Anchor Milk Powder is the major Anchor product available in some developing countries, such as Guyana and Ethiopia.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] Anchor Butter and Anchor Cheese are sold in New Zealand, but the brand for these products in New Zealand is still owned by a Goodman Fielder subsidiary.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] For butter and cheese the brand was not returned to Fonterra in the brand swap so not all Anchor branded products are Fonterra products in New Zealand.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] However, like most dairy products in New Zealand, the milk is still sourced from Fonterra suppliers and for butter and cheese, it is also likely that Fonterra manufactured the products with Goodman Fielder simply packaging the products.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] Internationally the Anchor brand is 100% owned by the Fonterra Co-Op Group.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] In Britain, Anchor block butter was imported from New Zealand until August 2012 when Arla Foods UK transferred production to a local factory in Westbury, Wiltshire, using English cream.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] Anchor Spreadable, as well as other New Zealand butter products, were banned from import into the EU for a short time.
[src:buttermilk/anchor-brand] This came after a complaint made to the European Commissioner for Trade, Peter Mandelson, by the German dairy trader, Egenberger.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] The lung disease bronchiolitis obliterans is attributed to prolonged exposure to diacetyl, e.g. in an industrial setting.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] Workers in several factories that manufacture artificial butter flavoring have been diagnosed with bronchiolitis obliterans, a rare and serious disease of the lungs.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] The disease has been called "popcorn worker's lung" or "popcorn lung" because it was first seen in former workers of a microwave popcorn factory in Missouri, but NIOSH refers to it by the more general term "flavorings-related lung disease".
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] It has also been called "flavorings-related bronchiolitis obliterans" or diacetyl-induced bronchiolitis obliterans.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] People who work with flavorings that include diacetyl are at risk for flavorings-related lung disease, including those who work in popcorn factories, restaurants, other snack food factories, bakeries, candy factories, margarine and cooking spread factories, and coffee processing facilities.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] In the year 2000, eight cases of bronchiolitis obliterans were detected in former employees of a microwave popcorn plant.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] Many of these individuals had initially been misdiagnosed as having other pulmonary diseases such as COPD and asthma.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] NIOSH investigated the worksite and suggested that artificial butter flavoring containing diacetyl was the most likely causative agent for the cases of bronchiolitis obliterans.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] Follow up investigations at the plant revealed that 25% of employees had abnormal spirometry exams.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] The plant effectively implemented changes reducing air concentrations of diacetyl by 1 to 3 orders of magnitude in the years following.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] A stabilization of respiratory symptoms was seen after this point in those who had been exposed to high levels of diacetyl.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] However, declines in lung function as measured by spirometry continued.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] Other studies also found cases of bronchiolitis obliterans in workers at 4 other microwave popcorn production facilities.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] Additionally further studies have demonstrated a large increase in abnormal spirometry values in workers exposed to flavoring chemicals with a clear dose-response relationship.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] In 2006, the International Brotherhood of Teamsters and the United Food and Commercial Workers petitioned the U.S.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] OSHA to promulgate an emergency temporary standard to protect workers from the deleterious health effects of inhaling diacetyl vapors.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] The petition was followed by a letter of support signed by more than 30 prominent scientists.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] On January 21, 2009, OSHA issued an advance notice of proposed rulemaking for regulating exposure to diacetyl.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] The notice requests respondents to provide input regarding adverse health effects, methods to evaluate and monitor exposure, and the training of workers.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] That notice also solicited input regarding exposure and health effects of acetoin, acetaldehyde, acetic acid and furfural.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] In 2007, two bills in the California Legislature sought to ban the use of diacetyl.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] The European Commission has declared diacetyl is legal for use as a flavouring substance in all EU states.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] As a diketone, diacetyl is included in the EU's flavouring classification Flavouring Group Evaluation 11 (FGE.11).
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] A Scientific Panel of the EU Commission evaluated six flavouring substances (not including diacetyl) from FGE.11 in 2004.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] As part of this study, the panel reviewed available studies on several other flavourings in FGE.11, including diacetyl.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] Based on the available data, the panel reiterated the finding that there were no safety concerns for diacetyl's use as a flavouring.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] In 2007, the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA), the EU's food safety regulatory body, stated its scientific panel on food additives and flavourings (AFC) was evaluating diacetyl along with other flavourings as part of a larger study.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] In 2007, the Flavor and Extract Manufacturers Association recommended reducing diacetyl in butter flavorings.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] Manufacturers of butter flavored popcorn including Pop Weaver, Trail's End, and ConAgra Foods (maker of Orville Redenbacher's and Act II) began removing diacetyl as an ingredient from their products.
[src:buttermilk/artificial-butter-flavoring] OSHA Safety and Health Information Bulletin and companion Worker Alert recommend employers use safety measures to minimize exposure to diacetyl or its substitutes.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] The modern concept of asepsis evolved in the 19th century through multiple individuals.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Ignaz Semmelweis showed already in 1847–1848 that hand washing prior to delivery reduced puerperal fever.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Despite this, many hospitals continued to practice surgery in unsanitary conditions, with some surgeons taking pride in their bloodstained operating gowns.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Only a decade later the situation started to change, when some French surgeons started to adopt carbolic acid as an antiseptic, reducing surgical infection rates, followed by their Italian colleagues in the 1860s.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] In 1867 Joseph Lister explained this reduction by Louis Pasteur's germ theory and popularized the disinfectant in the English-speaking world.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Giuseppe Ruggi shifted the movement then from antisepsis to asepsis in the 1870s, publishing his findings in 1879.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Gustav Adolf Neuber introduced sterile gowns and capes in 1883, and in 1891, Ernst von Bergmann introduced the autoclave, a device used for the practice of the sterilization of surgical instruments.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Rubber gloves were pioneered by William Halsted, who also implemented a no street clothes policy in his operating room, opting to wear a completely white, sterile uniform consisting of a duck suit, tennis shoes, and skullcap.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] This helped to prevent the introduction of infections into open wounds.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Additionally, Halsted would sterilize the operation site with disinfectants and use drapes to cover all areas except for the site.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] In his department at Johns Hopkins Hospital, he enforced an extreme hand washing ritual consisting of soaking in harmfully strong chemicals like permanganate and mercury bichloride solution as well as scrubbing with stiff brushes.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] The damage to a surgical nurse's hands compelled him to create the earliest form of the surgical gloves with the Goodyear Rubber Company.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] These gloves became a part of the aseptic surgery standard when Dr.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Joseph Colt Bloodgood and several others began wearing them for that particular purpose.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] The line between antisepsis and asepsis is interpreted differently, depending on context and time.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] In the past, antiseptic operations occurred in people's homes or in operating theaters before a large crowd.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Procedures for implementing antisepsis varied among physicians and experienced constant changes.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Until the late 19th century, physicians rejected the connection between Louis Pasteur's germ theory that bacteria caused diseases and antiseptic techniques.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Asepsis refers to any procedure that is performed under sterile conditions.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] This includes medical and laboratory techniques (such as with bacterial cultures).
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] There are two types of asepsis — medical and surgical.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Medical or clean asepsis reduces the number of organisms and prevents their spread; surgical or sterile asepsis includes procedures to eliminate micro-organisms from an area and is practiced by surgical technologists and nurses.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Ultimately, though, successful usage of aseptic operations depends on a combination of preparatory actions.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] For example, sterile equipment and fluids are used during invasive medical and nursing procedures.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] The largest manifestation of such aseptic techniques is in hospital operating theaters, where the aim is to keep patients free from hospital micro-organisms.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] While all members of the surgical team should demonstrate good aseptic technique, it is the role of the scrub nurse or surgical technologist to set up and maintain the sterile field.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] To prevent cross-contamination of patients, instruments are sterilized through autoclaving or by using disposable equipment; suture material or xenografts also need to be sterilized beforehand.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Basic aseptic procedures includes hand washing, donning protective gloves, masks and gowns, and sterilizing equipment and linens.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Medical aseptic techniques also includes curbing the spread of infectious diseases through quarantine, specifically isolation procedures based on the mode of disease transmission.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Within contact, droplet and airborne isolation methods, two different procedures emerge: strict isolation vs. reverse isolation.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Strict isolation quarantines patients to prevent them from infecting others, while reverse isolation prevents vulnerable patients from becoming infected.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] In aseptic conditions, a "chronic low-level inflammation" known as sterile inflammation may develop as a result of trauma, stress, or environmental factors.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] As in infections caused by pathogens or microbes, the immune response is regulated by host receptors.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Tissue damage resulting from non-infectious means are caused by DAMPs molecules released after injury or cell death has occurred, which are able to stimulate inflammation response.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Despite efforts to preserve asepsis during surgery, there still persists a 1-3% chance of a surgical site infection (SSI).
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] Infections are categorized as superficial incisional, deep incisional, or organ; the first type are confined to the skin, the second to muscles and nearby tissues, and the third to organs not anatomically close to the operation site.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] The exact modes of infection depend on the types of surgery, but the most common bacteria that are responsible for SSIs are Staphylococcus aureus, coagulase-negative staphylococci, Escherichia coli, and Enterococcus spp.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] The CDC emphasizes the importance of both antiseptic and aseptic approaches in avoiding SSIs, especially since Staphylococcus aureus, among other bacteria, are able to evolve drug-resistant strains that can be difficult to treat.
[src:buttermilk/aseptic] In 2017, nearly 20,000 patients in the United States died from Staphylococcus aureus in comparison to the 16,350 from diagnosed HIV.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] Ayran is served chilled and often as an accompaniment to grilled meat, bread or rice, especially during summer.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] It is made by mixing yogurt with chilled or iced water and is sometimes carbonated and seasoned with mint.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] It has been variously described as "diluted yogurt" and "a most refreshing drink made by mixing yogurt with iced water".
[src:buttermilk/ayran] The traditional method of preparing this drink among various Iranic peoples involves pouring yogurt into a waterskin—known as mashk (مشک) in Luri, Kurdish, and Persian, and maskah (مسکه) in Afghanistan —and vigorously shaking it to separate the butter from the liquid.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] The process takes a considerable amount of time and effort and is often made easier by suspending the waterskin from a wooden frame called *malār* (ملار) using woolen ropes, allowing it to swing freely.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] Once the butter is extracted, the remaining liquid, called doogh, is collected and consumed as a refreshing beverage.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] In Pakistan, ayran is called *Namkeen Lassi* (نمکین لسی).
[src:buttermilk/ayran] Ayran was developed in Central Asia by Turkic tribes.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] 1000 CE Turkic dictionary, *Dīwān ul-Lughat al-Turk*, defines *ayran* as a "drink made out of milk".
[src:buttermilk/ayran] Other similar but not identical drinks include doogh in Iran, *t’an* (Armenian: թան) in Armenia, and *lassi* in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] However, they can also differ from *doogh*.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] Salt, black pepper, dried mint, and lime juice can be mixed in.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] Diced cucumbers can be added to provide a crunchy texture to the beverage.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] In Balkan countries, the drink is usually consumed for breakfast or lunch, usually combined with pastries like banitsa, börek or other pastries.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] In Turkey, there are three types registered well known ayran variations one of them is *Susurluk Ayranı*.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] In this version ayran is drawn from the vat and rapidly poured back into it through a narrow pipe from above.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] During this circulation process, the fat in the ayran creates a foam on its surface.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] In some eastern parts of Turkey, ayran is made using a mixing method, which results in a very frothy drink which known as *Yayık Ayranı.* In Malatya region there is a form of spicy ayran known as *Malatya Spicy Ayran*.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] It has gained a registration and patent in 11.04.2022.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] In Afghanistan, ayran (known as *doogh* or *shromba*) is a summer beverage.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] It is made with yogurt, salt, mint, diced cucumbers, lime, and is sometimes carbonated.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] It is drunk alongside bolani, Afghan flatbread, and other picnic foods.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] In Albania, ayran is known as *dhallë* and is made exclusively with yogurt, salt and water and it is served cold.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] The name 'dhallë' comes from mixed and shaken.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] In Southern Cyprus *ayrani* (αϊρανι) is made with sour sheep yogurt, water, salt and mint.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] In Russia and some other Eastern Europe countries, a variant is called *kefir* which houses a similar taste but is instead made using fermented milk from kefir grains.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] The term may have derived from the Turkic word *köpür* ("to froth").
[src:buttermilk/ayran] Kefir is also popular in Turkey, though its consumption is less widespread than traditional fermented drinks such as ayran.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, a Turkish politician who has held the posts of President and Prime Minister, has promoted *ayran* as a national drink.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] Speaking at a 2013 WHO Global Alcohol Policy Conference held by simar in Istanbul, Erdoğan contrasted *ayran* with beer, which he claimed was a recent introduction to Turkey.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] Nevertheless, sales of *ayran* in Turkey lag behind other non-alcoholic beverages.
[src:buttermilk/ayran] According to a 2015 joint statement from the Soft Drink Producers Association, the Sparkling Water Producers Association, and the Milk Producers and Exporters Union of Turkey, *ayran* consumption during Ramadan had declined every year for the years 2010 to 2015.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Radio 4 is broadcast throughout the United Kingdom, the Isle of Man and the Channel Islands on FM, DAB and BBC Sounds, it can also be received in the eastern counties of Ireland, northern France and Northern Europe.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] It is available internationally via the BBC.com website and app.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] It currently reaches over 9.2 million listeners, making it the UK's second most-popular radio station after BBC Radio 2.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Radio 4 was previously broadcast on long wave on 198 kHz, from 23 November 1978 until 27 June 2026.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] BBC Radio 4 broadcasts news programmes such as *Today*, *The World at One*, *PM*, and *The Westminster Hour* heralded on air by the Greenwich Time Signal pips or the chimes of Big Ben, which are broadcast live.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Radio 4 also broadcasts the *Shipping Forecast*, which is over 150 years old.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] BBC Radio 4 broadcasts a wide variety of speech-related programming, including news, drama, comedy, science and history.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Music is broadcast as in documentaries relating to various forms of both popular and classical music, and the long-running music-based *Desert Island Discs*.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Sport is not part of the station's output, apart from during news bulletins, although between 1994 and 2023, the station's long wave frequency was used to broadcast ball-by-ball commentaries of most Test cricket matches played by England.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Consequently, for around 70 days a year, listeners had to rely on FM broadcasts or DAB for mainstream Radio 4 broadcasts – the number relying solely on long wave was now a small minority.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The cricket broadcasts took precedence over on-the-hour news bulletins, but not the *Shipping Forecast*, carried since Radio 4's move to long wave in 1978 because long wave can be received clearly at sea.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Freesat, Sky and Virgin formerly had a separate channel for Radio 4 LW output in mono, in addition to the FM output, but these were removed after the separate schedule for LW ended in April 2024.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] BBC Radio 4 is the second-most-popular British domestic radio station by total hours, after Radio 2.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] It recorded its highest audience, of 11 million listeners, in May 2011, and was "UK Radio Station of the Year" at the 2003, 2004, 2008 and 2023 Radio Academy Awards.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] It also won a Peabody Award in 2002 for *File on 4: Export Controls*.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Costing £87 million (2024/5), it is the BBC's most expensive national radio network.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] There is no comparable British commercial network: Channel 4 abandoned plans to launch its own speech-based digital radio station in October 2008 as part of a £100m cost-cutting review.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The long wave signal was part of the Royal Navy's system of letters of last resort.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] In the event of a suspected catastrophic attack on Britain, submarine captains, in addition to other checks, check for a broadcast signal from Radio 4 on 198 kHz long wave to verify the destruction of organised society in the United Kingdom.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Initially the power was 100 watts on 350 metres (857 kHz).
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] 2LO was allowed to transmit for seven minutes, after which the "operator" had to listen on the wavelength for three minutes for possible instructions to close down.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] On 14 November 1922, the station was transferred to the new British Broadcasting Company, which in 1923 took up the nearby Savoy Hill for its broadcasting studios.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] At midnight on New Year's Eve 1923, the twelve chimes of Big Ben were broadcast for the first time to mark the new year.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] While it was possible to combine large numbers of trunk telephone lines to link transmitters for individual programmes, the process was expensive and not encouraged by the General Post Office as it tied up large parts of the telephone network.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The stations that followed the establishment of 2LO in London were therefore autonomously programmed using local talent and facilities.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] By May 1923, simultaneous broadcasting was technically possible at least between main transmitters and relay stations, the quality was not felt to be high enough to provide a national service or regular simultaneous broadcasts.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] In 1924, it was felt that technical standards had improved enough for London to start to provide the majority of the output, cutting the local stations back to providing items of local interest.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The company became the British Broadcasting Corporation in 1927.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] On 9 March 1930, 2LO was replaced by the BBC Regional Programme and the BBC National Programme.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The letters *LO* continued to be used internally as a designation in the BBC for technical operations in the London area (for example, the numbering of all recordings made in London contained *LO*).
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The code *LO* was changed to *LN* in the early 1970s.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The BBC Home Service was the predecessor of Radio 4 and broadcast between 1939 and 1967.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] It had regional variations and was broadcast on medium wave with a network of VHF FM transmitters being added from 1955.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Radio 4 replaced it on 30 September 1967, when the BBC restructured and renamed its domestic radio stations, in response to the challenge of offshore radio.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] It moved to long wave in November 1978, taking over the 200 kHz frequency (1,500 metres) previously held by Radio 2 - later moved to 198 kHz as a result of international agreements aimed at avoiding interference (all ITU Region 1 MW/LW broadcast frequencies are divisible by 9).
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] At this point, Radio 4 became available across all of the UK for the first time and the station officially became known as Radio 4 UK, a title that remained until 29 September 1984.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] For a time during the 1970s, Radio 4 carried regional news bulletins Monday to Saturday.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] These were broadcast twice at breakfast, at lunchtime and at 17:55.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] There were also programme variations for the parts of England not served by BBC Local Radio stations.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] These included *Roundabout East Anglia*, a VHF opt-out of the *Today* programme broadcast from BBC East's studios in Norwich each weekday from 06:45{ to 08:45.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] *Roundabout East Anglia* came to an end in August 1980, ahead of the launch of BBC Radio Norfolk.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The launch of Radio 5 on 27 August 1990 saw the removal of Open University, schools programming, children's programmes and the *Study on 4*/*Options* adult education slot from Radio 4's FM frequencies.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Consequently, the full Radio 4 schedule became available on FM for the first time.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] However, adult educational and Open University programming returned to Radio 4 in 1994, when Radio 5 was closed to make way for the launch of BBC Radio 5 Live and were broadcast until the end of the 1990s, on Sunday evenings on long wave only.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Between 17 January 1991 and 2 March 1991, FM broadcasts were replaced by a continuous news service devoted to the Gulf War, Radio 4 News FM, with the main Radio 4 service transferring to long wave.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Before this, Radio 4's FM frequencies had occasionally been used for additional news coverage, generally for live coverage of statements and debates in Parliament.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] By the start of the 1990s, Radio 4 had become available on FM in most of the UK - previously FM coverage had been restricted mainly to England and south Wales.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] However, 1994 did see the end of the extra news coverage on long wave due to the launch of BBC Radio 5 Live, although occasional broadcasts of services continued with the last being when Pope Benedict XVI visited Britain in 2010.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] On 15 April 2024 at 12:27 BST, Radio 4's medium wave frequencies were switched off.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] These previously served as relays in areas with a weak long wave signal to provide reception of Radio 4 long wave, such as Northern Ireland and south west England.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] A continuous closedown loop message was broadcast until 30 April 2024, informing listeners to retune to other methods of reception.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] On 30 May 2023, the BBC announced that Radio 4 will stop broadcasting opt-outs on long wave with the last opt-outs airing on 31 March 2024.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The two displaced programmes, *Daily Service* and *Yesterday in Parliament* moved to BBC Radio 4 Extra, although the latter was returned to the early morning Radio 4 schedule in April 2025.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The daily amount of *Shipping Forecasts* was reduced to be broadcast 2 times on weekdays and 3 times on weekends.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] *Test Match Special* moved to BBC Radio 5 Sports Extra on 31 July 2023.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] These end ahead of a planned switch-off of long wave transmissions by 26 September 2026.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] On 11 May 2026, the BBC announced that Radio 4 long wave transmission would be switched-off earlier than previously publicised, on 27 June 2026.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] At 01:00 BST, the long wave transmitters were switched off as planned, and a retune loop began playing on 198 kHz, and is expected to continue doing so until its permanent switch-off on 30 June 2026.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] As of April 2025, Radio 4 is on air from 05:00 to 01:00 every Monday to Friday, and 05:30 to 01:00 every Saturday and Sunday.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The station simulcasts the BBC World Service during its downtime overnight including Newsday (Radio).
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] An online schedule page lists the running order of programmes.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The station broadcasts a mix of live and pre-recorded programmes.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Live programming includes breakfast programme *Today*, magazine programme *Woman's Hour*, consumer affairs programme *You and Yours*, and (often) the music, film, books, arts and culture programme *Front Row*.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The news returning to Broadcasting House has also meant that newsreaders can provide cover for continuity, which regularly occurs at 23:00 each night and 16:00 on a Sunday.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] This has reduced the total number of continuity announcers required each day down from four to three.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The Greenwich Time Signal, popularly known as "the pips", is broadcast virtually every hour to herald the news bulletin, except at midnight and 18:00, and 22:00 on Sunday, when the chimes of Big Ben are played.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] There is no Greenwich Time Signal at 15:00 on Saturday or 11:00 and 12:00 on Sunday due to the Saturday Afternoon drama and the omnibus edition of *The Archers* respectively.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Only pips broadcast on FM and LW are accurate.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] On digital platforms there is a delay of between three and five seconds, and up to 23 seconds online.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Radio 4 programmes cover a wide variety of genre including news and current affairs, history, culture, science, religion, arts, comedy, drama and entertainment.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] A number of the programmes on Radio 4 take the form of a "magazine" show, featuring numerous small contributions over the course of the programme—*Woman's Hour*, *From Our Own Correspondent*, *You and Yours*.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The rise of these magazine shows is primarily due to the work of Tony Whitby, controller of Radio 4 from 1970 to 1975.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The station hosts a number of long-running programmes, many of which have been broadcast for over 40 years.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Most programmes are available to UK listeners for 30 days or over a year after broadcast as streaming audio from Radio 4's *Listen again* page and via BBC Sounds.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] The *Listen again* page is essential for overseas listeners in different time zones as it enables them to hear programmes at a reasonable hour.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] In July 2025, the BBC blocked its non-UK audience (approximately 300,000 listeners) from using *Listen again*.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] In response to listeners’ complaints, the BBC reversed itself the following month.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] On 7 August, it was announced on Radio 4’s *Feedback* that *Listen again* (aka ‘On demand’) would be restored for its overseas Radio 4 and World Service listeners.But as of January 2026, the BBC provides *Listen again* to overseas listeners for fewer than half its Radio 4 programmes.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Many comedy and drama programmes from the Radio 4 archives are broadcast on BBC Radio 4 Extra.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] 704), Sky, Virgin and on line via BBC Sounds.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] BBC World Service, which uses BBC Radio 4 FM & DAB frequencies between 01:00 and 05:20, is in stereo, but only on Radio 4 FM & DAB and not on its own dedicated DAB channel.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] BBC Radio 4 Extra broadcasts in mono on DAB, but has always been in stereo on Digital TV (Freeview / Freesat Ch 708), Sky, Virgin and online.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Newsreaders read hourly summaries and longer bulletins from New Broadcasting House.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] In 2012 the BBC announced that it would be reducing its main presentation team from 12 to ten.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Criticism voiced by centre-right newspapers in recent years have a perceived left political bias across a range of issues, as well as sycophancy in interviews, particularly on the popular morning news magazine *Today* as part of a reported perception of a general "malaise" at the BBC.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Conversely, the journalist Mehdi Hasan has criticised the station for an overtly "socially and culturally conservative" approach.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] There has been criticism of *Today* in particular for a lack of female broadcasters.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] In September 1972, Radio 4 employed the first female continuity announcers—Hylda Bamber and Barbara Edwards.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] For quite some time, the introduction of female newsreaders led to complaints from listeners; women discussing topics of feminist interest led to similar complaints.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] In addition, there has been long-running criticism by atheist and humanist groups of *Thought for the Day*, a slot dedicated exclusively to religious discussion during Radio 4's flagship morning news programme.
[src:buttermilk/bbc-radio-4] Radio 4 has been criticised for being "too middle class" and of "little interest" to non-white listeners.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Buttermilk is consumed as a beverage and used in cooking.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Drinking buttermilk remains common in warmer climates where unrefrigerated milk sours quickly, as the fermentation prevents further spoilage.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] In making soda bread, the acid in fermented buttermilk reacts with the leavening agent, sodium bicarbonate (baking soda), to produce carbon dioxide.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Buttermilk is used in marination, especially for chicken and pork.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Buttermilk originated before the advent of refrigeration and homogenization, when fresh raw milk was left to stand for a period of time to allow the cream to separate to the top.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] During the separation period, naturally occurring lactic acid-producing bacteria in the milk ferment it, which facilitates the butter churning process, because fat from cream with a lower pH coalesces more readily than that of fresh cream.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] As this acidic environment also helps prevent potentially harmful microorganisms from growing, shelf life is increased.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] This traditional method is susceptible to spoilage during the fermenting and churning processes, particularly under poor hygiene standards and when it is not kept cool.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Refrigeration and the use of fresh milk in near-aseptically clean dairies largely eliminated these problems.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Traditional buttermilk is still common in many households across South Asia, the Middle East, and various parts of Europe but is seldom found in other Western countries.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] In Arab culture, buttermilk is commonly sold ice cold with other dairy products and often consumed during Ramadan for *iftar* and *suhur*, while in the Indian subcontinent, it may be served with roasted maize.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] The lactic acid is the product of the bacteria fermenting lactose, the primary sugar in milk.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] As the bacteria produce lactic acid, the pH of the milk decreases and casein, the primary milk protein, precipitates, causing the curdling or clabbering of milk, making cultured buttermilk thicker than plain milk.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] While both traditional and cultured buttermilk contain lactic acid, traditional buttermilk is thinner than cultured buttermilk.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Cultured buttermilk was first commercially introduced in the United States in the 1920s.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] It was initially consumed among immigrants.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Consumption of buttermilk has declined since then, and annual sales in 2012 reached less than half that number.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] However, condensed buttermilk and dried buttermilk remain common in the food industry.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Liquid buttermilk is used primarily in the commercial preparation of baked goods and cheese.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Buttermilk solids are used in ice cream manufacturing, as well as being added to pancake mixes to make buttermilk pancakes.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Home cooks can use powdered buttermilk to give baked goods a higher rise, add tang to dips, marinades, and rubs without thinning them out, and as a topping for fruits and vegetables.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Traditional buttermilk has only trace levels of fat – less than 0.5 percent.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Modern commercially produced buttermilk made with whole milk is 88% water, 3% protein, 3% fat, and 5% carbohydrates (see table).
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz) (100 ml), whole buttermilk provides 62 calories of food energy, and is a moderate source of vitamin B12 (19% DV) and riboflavin (13% DV, table).
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] Acidified buttermilk or acidulated buttermilk is a substitute made by adding a food-grade acid, such as distilled white vinegar or lemon juice, to milk and letting it stand for about 10 minutes until it curdles.
[src:buttermilk/buttermilk] (About 15 millilitres (0.5 imperial fluid ounces; 0.5 US fluid ounces) of acid is added 200 to 250 ml (7 to 9 imp fl oz; 7 to 8 US fl oz) of milk.) Milk with any amount of fat can be used, but whole milk is usually used for baking.
